13,10,11,12]\nOutput: 33\nExplanation: [10,11,12] is the ascending subarray with the maximum sum of 33.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 100\n1 <= nums[i] <= 100\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxAscendingSum(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxAscendingSum(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        if not nums:\n            return 0\n        \n        max_sum = current_sum = nums[0]\n        \n        for i in range(1, len(nums)):\n            if nums[i] > nums[i - 1]:\n                current_sum += nums[i]\n            else:\n                max_sum = max(max_sum, current_sum)\n                current_sum = nums[i]\n        \n        # Final check to ensure the last subarray is considered\n        max_sum = max(max_sum, current_sum)\n        \n        return max_sum\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the list of numbers, maintaining a running sum of the current ascending subarray. When it encounters a number that is not greater than the previous one, it compares the current sum to the maximum sum found so far and resets the current sum. Finally, it ensures the last subarray is considered by comparing it once more at the end.", "estimated_date": 1616284800000}